Introduction [id=fba3_intro_section]
------------

::fba3_introduction [display=target:psych_sba_sidebar4auto label="Introduction"]

Annie: Okay, so... I have good news and bad news about Johnny. [face=concerned]

JJ: Oh no. Bad news first. [face=concernedFear]

Annie: The bad news is that things actually got worse over the two weeks. My roommate tracked everything in her journal like we said — she babysat 5 times, and Johnny only went to bed on time twice. And she noticed the escape behaviors getting worse, not better. [face=fear]

Lin: Worse? But the plan was solid — we based it on the right function, we used antecedent strategies. What happened? [face=serious]

Annie: That's kind of the thing. On at least one of the bad nights, she admitted she didn't exactly follow the plan. [face=concerned]

JJ: "Didn't exactly follow the plan." I have a feeling that's going to be important. [face=explaining]

Progress Monitoring [id=fba3_progress_section]
-------------------

::fba3_predict_fidelity [display=target:psych_sba_sidebar4auto label="Progress Data"]

--- wait @fba3_interpretation_confidence.value ---

Lin: Let's bring this to Lianne. We need more resources if we're going to figure out what went wrong. [face=serious]

Annie: We showed her the graph and explained that my roommate admitted she hadn't followed all of the consequence strategies.

Lianne: That's actually a very common issue. It sounds like you need to think about implementation fidelity. [face=calm]

Implementation Fidelity [id=fba3_fidelity_section]
------------------------

Lin: Based on what Lianne shared, implementation fidelity refers to how accurately and consistently a behavior plan is implemented as it was designed. It's not just about having a good plan — it's about whether the plan was actually carried out. [face=serious]

JJ: So the question is: was Annie's roommate actually doing what our plan said she should do? Step by step, consistently? [face=explaining]

::fba3_fidelity_tabs [display=target:psych_sba_sidebar4auto label="Practice Fidelity Concepts"]

Annie: Okay, this is making sense. The plan might be fine — the problem might be in the execution. Let me text my roommate and find out exactly where things broke down.

Fidelity Check [id=fba3_fidelity_check_section]
---------------

::fba3_fidelity_check [display=target:psych_sba_sidebar4auto label="Diagnose the Fidelity Issue"]

Annie: She got back to me with details. Last Thursday was the worst night. She started the bedtime routine at 7:45, but she forgot the 5-minute warning completely — just went straight to "time for bed." No timer, either. Johnny immediately ran to the living room. [face=concerned]

Annie: She said she tried to stay calm, but after about ten minutes of him running around, she started bargaining — "If you go to bed right now, you can have extra screen time tomorrow." He whined that bedtime was unfair, and she ended up going back and forth with him for another fifteen minutes before he finally wore himself out. [face=fear]

Lin: So she skipped the antecedent steps, and then reinforced the escape behavior by negotiating. That's essentially the opposite of the plan. [face=serious]

Annie: She also says she sometimes forgets the small bedtime reward even on the good nights. She's a college student with a full course load — she's not trying to mess this up, she just has a lot going on. [face=concerned]

--- wait @fba3_fidelity_choice.submitCount > 0 ---

Improving Adherence [id=fba3_adherence_section]
--------------------

JJ: So the main issue is adherence — she's not consistently following the plan steps. [face=explaining]

Lin: Right. And now we can see exactly why it matters. Without the warning and the timer, Johnny doesn't get the antecedent cues that make bedtime predictable. And every time she negotiates, she's actually reinforcing the escape — he learns that whining and running gets him a conversation instead of bedtime. [face=serious]

JJ: Honestly, I'm starting to think we need to redesign the whole plan. Maybe it's too complicated. We could simplify it, streamline the steps, maybe build in some kind of automated— [face=explaining]

Lin: Hold on. Before we throw out the plan, let's figure out whether the problem is really the plan or whether it's the implementation. Those are two very different problems with very different solutions. [face=serious]

JJ: I mean, if she can't follow it, doesn't that mean it's not a good plan?

Lianne: That's a good question, JJ. But think about it this way — if a patient doesn't take their medication, do you change the medication, or do you figure out why they're not taking it? Sometimes the answer is one, sometimes the other, and sometimes both. But you have to diagnose before you prescribe. [face=calm]

JJ: ...Fair point. Okay, let's diagnose first. [face=smile]

JJ: I tried asking AI for help with this, but my first prompt was just "How can I improve adherence to the intervention plan?" — and I got back this really long, generic list that could apply to anything. [face=concerned]

Lin: That's because you didn't give it any context. The AI doesn't know we're talking about a specific child with escape-maintained bedtime behavior being implemented by a busy college student. Without that background, it's just filling in blanks with generic advice. [face=serious]

JJ: What kind of context does it need?

Lianne: Think about what makes your situation specific. The AI should know this is an operant conditioning intervention, what the plan actually involves, and what specific problems the roommate is having. The more specific your input, the more useful the output. [face=calm]

Annie: Right — we can't just say "help me fix the plan." We have to lay out the whole picture. Let's be really explicit this time. [face=smile]

::fba3_ai_adherence [display=target:psych_sba_sidebar4auto label="Ask AI About Adherence"]

--- wait @fba3_ai_adherence_response.value ---

Modifications [id=fba3_modifications_section]
--------------

::fba3_modifications_display [display=target:psych_sba_sidebar4auto label="Modification Ideas"]

JJ: Much better this time — these suggestions are actually specific to our situation! [face=smile]

Annie: It is a lot, though. We should read through carefully and make sure everything lines up with what we've actually learned. AI can sound confident even when it's off-base. [face=serious]

::fba3_checklist_display [display=target:psych_sba_sidebar4auto label="Fidelity Checklist"]

Lin: Here's a fidelity checklist we can give to Annie's roommate. It covers the main bedtime routine steps — things like the warning countdown, the timer, the reward.

JJ: And I added some items about how to respond when escape behaviors happen — like not chasing, not negotiating. That was where the roommate was struggling most. [face=explaining]

::fba3_modification_selection [display=target:psych_sba_sidebar4auto label="Choose Modifications"]

Annie: Okay, of these modifications, which ones do you think would actually help my roommate the most? Pick up to 2.

--- wait @fba3_modification_explanation.value ---

